## §2 — DOCUMENT CHECK

Perform a structural and formal check of the submitted document.
Do not evaluate content in this section — observe and record only.

### 2.1 Basic identification

- submission_language:
    What language is the submission written in?
    [Detect. If mixed-language or unclear, state which sections use
    which language. Note if this differs from any language requirement
    in {{SEMINAR_REQUIREMENTS}}.]

- document_type:
    [thesis | seminar-paper | essay | report | portfolio | other —
     specify]
    Cross-reference with {{SEMINAR_REQUIREMENTS}} — does the document
    type match what was requested?

- approximate_word_count:
    Count words in the main body only. Exclude: title page, abstract,
    reference list, appendices.
    [Provide count. Flag if significantly above or below any length
    requirement in {{INSTITUTION_FRAMEWORK}} or {{SEMINAR_REQUIREMENTS}}.]

- modality:
    [text-only | multimodal]
    If multimodal: list all non-text elements present (images, diagrams,
    tables, data visualisations, appendices). Note which elements are
    integral to the argument and which are supplementary.
    If text-only: state "Text-only submission."

### 2.2 Structural elements check

For each element: state [present | absent | present-but-underdeveloped |
not-required-by-brief].
Add a brief note only if the status requires explanation.

  abstract:               [status] — [note or omit]
  introduction:           [status] — [note or omit]
  theoretical-framework:  [status] — [note or omit]
  methodology:            [status] — [note or omit]
  analysis / main-body:   [status] — [note or omit]
  discussion:             [status] — [note or omit]
  conclusion:             [status] — [note or omit]
  reference-list:         [status] — [note or omit]
  appendices:             [status] — [note or omit]

### 2.3 Formal compliance check

Cross-reference the submission against formal requirements in
{{INSTITUTION_FRAMEWORK}} and {{SEMINAR_REQUIREMENTS}}.
For each formal requirement identified (length, format, citation style,
language of submission, structure, anonymisation, etc.):

  - req_ref:   [cite the requirement source: programme | seminar]
  - requirement: [state the formal requirement precisely]
  - status:    [met | not-met | partially-met | cannot-assess]
  - note:      [brief note, or omit]

### 2.4 Notable gaps vs requirements

What is conspicuously absent from the submission relative to stated
requirements? Observe only — evaluation follows in §5.

For each gap identified:
  - gap_id:          [G1, G2, …]
  - description:     [What is missing and why it is conspicuous
                      relative to the stated requirements]
  - severity:        [structural | content | formal]
  - from_requirement: [Cite the specific requirement from §1 that
                       makes this absence notable]

If no notable gaps identified, state: "No notable gaps detected."

