## §3 — CORE ARGUMENT ANALYSIS

Identify and articulate the student's core argument. Focus on what
the submission actually argues — not what the requirements say it
should argue. Record findings in {{OUTPUT_LANGUAGE}}.

### 3.1 Thesis identification

- thesis_present:
    [yes | unclear | no]

- thesis_text:
    State the central argument in 1–3 sentences.
    If unclear: describe what appears to be the central claim and
    explain why it is unclear.
    If absent: state "No identifiable thesis detected" and note
    whether the submission has a de facto implicit argument instead.

- thesis_location:
    [introduction | abstract | conclusion | scattered | absent]
    If scattered: cite the 2–3 locations where thesis-equivalent
    statements appear.

- thesis_confidence:
    [high | medium | low]
    Justify in one sentence.

### 3.2 Supporting claims

For each major claim that supports, develops, or is required for
the thesis, provide:

  - claim_id:      [C1, C2, …]
  - claim_text:    [The claim in clear, standardised language.
                    Do not quote verbatim — paraphrase and cite
                    location.]
  - claim_type:    [thesis-support | methodological | descriptive |
                    conclusion]
  - evidence_basis: [cited-source | original-analysis |
                     empirical-data | assumed | unclear]
  - connection_to_thesis: [strong | weak | unclear | absent]
  - confidence:    [high | medium | low]

Scope: extract the claims that matter for the argument — typically
5–10 for a standard academic submission. Do not extract every
observation in the text.

### 3.3 Argument structure summary

In 2–4 sentences: Is there a coherent argument from thesis through
supporting claims to conclusion? Where does the argumentative chain
break or weaken? Are supporting claims additive (they build the
argument together) or redundant (they repeat the same point)?

