## §5 — REQUIREMENTS ALIGNMENT

This is the core assessment section. Systematically evaluate the
submission against each stated requirement from §1.

For each requirement: cite evidence from the submission. Do not assert
alignment without grounding it in what the submission actually contains.

### 5.1 Programme requirements alignment

Source: {{INSTITUTION_FRAMEWORK}}

For each requirement extracted from the institutional framework:

  - req_id:      [P1, P2, …]
  - requirement: [Quote or paraphrase the requirement precisely.
                  Do not interpret or expand — state it as given.]
  - status:      [met | partially-met | not-met | not-assessable]
  - evidence:    [Cite specific text, section, or structural observation
                  from the submission that supports this judgment.
                  Use format: "§[section], para [N]: '[brief quote]'"
                  or "Reference list: [observation]".]
  - confidence:  [high | medium | low]
  - note:        [Any nuance the teacher should know — e.g. borderline
                  judgment, conflicting signals, or limitation on
                  confidence. If no note needed, omit.]

### 5.2 Seminar requirements alignment

Source: {{SEMINAR_REQUIREMENTS}}

For each requirement extracted from the seminar/course criteria:

  - req_id:      [S1, S2, …]
  - requirement: [Quote or paraphrase precisely.]
  - status:      [met | partially-met | not-met | not-assessable]
  - evidence:    [Cite as above.]
  - confidence:  [high | medium | low]
  - note:        [As above, or omit.]

### 5.3 Alignment summary

- fully_met_count:       [N]
- partially_met_count:   [N]
- not_met_count:         [N]
- not_assessable_count:  [N]

- critical_gaps:
    List the req_ids of requirements assessed as not-met that are
    likely to be load-bearing for the teacher's grade decision.
    If none: state "No requirements assessed as entirely unmet."

- confidence_in_alignment_section:
    [high | medium | low]
    State what limits or supports confidence in this section as a whole.
    Common limiters: ambiguous requirements in §1, configuration issues,
    missing content in submission, non-text elements not assessable.

