## §6 — ASSESSMENT REPORT

Write the assessment report in {{OUTPUT_LANGUAGE}}.
This section is written for the teacher, not for the record. Use
clear, direct professional language. The teacher is an expert — write
as a well-informed colleague, not as a system log.

### 6.1 Overall impression

1–2 sentences. State the overall quality of the submission at the
level an experienced teacher would summarise it to a colleague.
Do not hedge every word — state your finding clearly, noting
confidence where it genuinely matters.

### 6.2 Strengths

List up to 5 genuine strengths. For each: a specific finding with
a location reference or quote from the submission. Do not list
strengths that are not genuinely present in the submission — if
there are fewer than 5, list fewer.

  [S-1] …
  [S-2] …
  [add as needed — maximum 5]

### 6.3 Areas for development

List the most significant areas where the work falls short of
requirements or of academic expectations for its level. For each:
a specific finding with evidence, and a concrete indication of what
adequate development would look like.

  [D-1] …
  [D-2] …
  [add as needed]

### 6.4 Unmet requirements

List all requirements with status = not-met from §5.
For each:

  [U-N] Requirement: [req_id — text] | Evidence: [brief] |
        Note: [anything the teacher should know before deciding]

If all requirements are met or partially-met, state:
"No requirements were assessed as entirely unmet."

### 6.5 Assessment confidence

- confidence_level:   [high | medium | low]
- rationale:          2–3 sentences explaining what limits or supports
                      confidence in this assessment overall.
- cannot_assess:      List what could not be assessed and why (e.g.
                      visual content in text-only mode, missing sections,
                      ambiguous requirements). If nothing is unassessable,
                      state: "No significant unassessable elements."

